Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog** — Override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell.xaml.cs` using `GetDeferral()`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — In `EditProductPage.xaml`, use `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel (or code-behind), the command triggers the same guard logic:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This navigates back, which triggers OnNavigating above
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks (the `DisplayAlert`). Without it you get race conditions.
- `args.Cancel()` prevents navigation if the user chooses "Stay".
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back-arrow tap, so navigation only happens if your command calls `GoToAsync("..")`.
